<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-slight-mistake" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>A slight adjustment to the confidence interval formula</title>
    <p>
        The confidence interval formula introduced in the previous section provides a useful way to
        understand how confidence intervals are constructed. However, there is one important detail.
        The formula uses the population standard deviation, <m>\sigma</m>, when calculating the
        standard error. In practice, the population standard deviation is almost never known and must
        instead be estimated from the sample.
    </p>
    <p>
        Replacing the unknown population standard deviation with the sample standard deviation
        introduces additional uncertainty into the estimate. To account for this uncertainty,
        confidence intervals are calculated using the <em>t-distribution</em> rather than the normal
        distribution. The <em>t</em>-distribution is similar to the normal distribution but has
        slightly heavier tails, resulting in wider confidence intervals, particularly when the sample
        size is small.
    </p>
    <p>
        As the sample size increases, the estimate of the population standard deviation becomes more
        reliable. Consequently, the <em>t</em>-distribution approaches the normal distribution, and
        the difference between the two becomes negligible. For large samples, confidence intervals
        calculated using the <em>t</em>-distribution are therefore almost identical to those based on
        the normal distribution.
    </p>
    <p>
        In practice, there is no need to determine which distribution to use manually. R-Instat
        automatically applies the appropriate method when calculating confidence intervals. The
        important point is that smaller samples produce wider confidence intervals because they
        provide less precise information about the population, whereas larger samples produce narrower
        confidence intervals because the estimates are more reliable.
    </p>    
</subsection>